04239nam a22005895i 9780822387589DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223875897 a10.1515/97808223875892doi  a(DE-B1597)554419  a(OCoLC)1167158707  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aB841.4b.C46 2006 7aPHI0310002bisacsh04a149.9222  aCC 48002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17631:1 aChow, Rey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Age of the World Target :bSelf-Referentiality in War, Theory, and Comparative Work /cRey Chow; Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan, Inderpal Grewal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (140 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave Provocations00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. European Theory in America -- tI. The Age of the World Target: Atomic Bombs, Alterity, Area Studies -- tII. The Interruption of Referentiality; or, Poststructuralism's Outside -- tIII. The Old/New Question of Comparison in Literary Studies: A Post-European Perspective -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMartin Heidegger once wrote that the world had, in the age of modern science, become a world picture. For Rey Chow, the world has, in the age of atomic bombs, become a world target, to be attacked once it is identified, or so global geopolitics, dominated by the United States since the end of the Second World War, seems repeatedly to confirm. How to articulate the problematics of knowledge production with this aggressive targeting of the world? Chow attempts such an articulation by probing the significance of the chronological proximity of area studies, poststructuralist theory, and comparative literature-fields of inquiry that have each exerted considerable influence but whose mutual implicatedness as postwar U.S. academic phenomena has seldom been theorized. Central to Chow's discussions is a critique of the predicament of self-referentiality-the compulsive move to interiorize that, in her view, constitutes the collective frenzy of our age-in different contemporary epistemic registers, including the self-consciously avant-garde as well as the militaristic and culturally supremacist. Urging her readers to think beyond the inward-turning focus on EuroAmerica that tends to characterize even the most radical gestures of Western self-deconstruction, Chow envisions much broader intellectual premises for future transcultural work, with reading practices aimed at restoring words and things to their constitutive exteriority.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aPoststructuralism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / General.2bisacsh1 aGrewal, Inderpal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387589zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822387589.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles